# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Public origin (used by metadataBase, sitemap, robots). Set to your
# production URL on Vercel (e.g. https://openspot.vercel.app).
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
APP_URL=https://openspot.example.com

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OpenWeather (current weather + forecast + icons)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
URL_WEATHER=https://api.openweathermap.org
URL_WEATHER_IMG=https://openweathermap.org/payload/api/media/file
API_KEY_WEATHER=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Nominatim (OpenStreetMap geocoder, autocomplete, reverse, nearby)
# Required User-Agent per Nominatim Usage Policy: descriptive, with a contact
# channel.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
NOMINATIM_URL=https://nominatim.openstreetmap.org
NOMINATIM_USER_AGENT=open-spot-website/1.0 (contact@example.com)

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Postgres — SINGLE SOURCE OF CONNECTION for dev and Vercel.
#
# The runtime (Drizzle client), the build (none — see AGENTS.md), and the
# dev-console scripts (`pnpm db:seed`, `pnpm db:apply`, `pnpm db:health`)
# all read through `getDatabaseUrl()`, which resolves `SUPABASE_DATABASE_URL`
# first. Set this in BOTH `.env.local` (for `pnpm dev`) and Vercel (for
# production). Local dev and Vercel use the same Supabase project, so the
# value is the same string in both environments.
#
# Why the pooler (and not the direct endpoint)?
#   The direct hostname `db.<project>.supabase.co` (port 5432) is not
#   DNS-resolvable from the Vercel function network. The pooler hostname
#   `aws-0-<region>.pooler.supabase.com` (port 6543) is IPv4-only, designed
#   for serverless, and resolves correctly from Vercel. Same Postgres, same
#   RLS, same schema — just a different endpoint.
#
# Transaction vs Session pooler mode:
#   The Supabase dashboard exposes two pooler modes at the same host and
#   port. Pick **Mode: Transaction** — pgBouncer releases the server
#   connection back to the pool after each SQL transaction, which is the
#   only mode that works for serverless. The **Session** mode pooler holds
#   a server connection for the entire client session and saturates the
#   pool fast under Vercel concurrency (error: `EMAXCONNSESSION ... max
#   clients reached in session mode - max clients are limited to
#   pool_size: 15`). The Supabase dashboard labels the dropdown "Mode".
#
# Get the connection string from:
#   Supabase dashboard → Project → Settings → Database → Connection string
#   → "Transaction" pooler (port 6543, mode: Transaction).
#
# Resolution order in `getDatabaseUrl()`:
#   1. SUPABASE_DATABASE_URL  <- the pooler, the runtime default
#   2. SUPABASE_DIRECT_URL    <- direct, local DDL only (never set on Vercel)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
SUPABASE_DATABASE_URL=
# SUPABASE_DIRECT_URL=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Supabase (auth + admin)
#
# When you wire the app to a Supabase project, set the env vars below in
# BOTH `.env.local` (for `pnpm dev`) and Vercel (for production). See
# DEPLOY.md for the exact Vercel env list and the bucket-creation step.
#
# The keys live in your project's dashboard at:
#   https://supabase.com/dashboard/project/<ref>/settings/api-keys
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# REQUIRED for auth. The publishable key (`sb_publishable_...`) is safe
# to expose to the browser; the @supabase/ssr SSR client and the Next.js
# proxy both use it.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=

# Server-only. NEVER prefix with NEXT_PUBLIC_ or expose to the bundle.
# The secret key (`sb_secret_...`) is used only by `getAdminClient()`
# in src/lib/auth.ts to upsert into `public.profiles` while bypassing
# RLS.
SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY=

# Storage bucket for user-contributed spot images. Must match the bucket
# created in the Supabase dashboard (see DEPLOY.md step 1). Defaults to
# "spot-images".
# SUPABASE_STORAGE_BUCKET_SPOTS=spot-images

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Admin allow-list (CSV of emails, case-insensitive). When Supabase is
# unconfigured the dev placeholder user is automatically treated as
# admin (see `isAdminUser` in `@/lib/admin.ts`). Set this to grant admin
# access to specific Google-auth users when Supabase is configured.
#   Example: ADMIN_EMAILS=alice@example.com,bob@example.com
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ADMIN_EMAILS=devopenspot@gmail.com
